To assume, on the other hand, that the Eyrie really served as the refuge of a band of criminals, seemed absurd.
If they feared that the police would discover their retreat, surely they would not have been so foolish as thus to force attention upon themselves.
Their chief security would lie in keeping their presence there unknown.
They must have realized that such a challenge from them would only arouse the police to renewed activity.
